\begin_layout Standard
I think this has to do with the models not being the same,
 i.e.,
 there is no information telling us there is a latent 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\star}$
\end_inset

 in the Bayesian framework.
 The question is how to rectify this.
 The observed data is 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x,y)$
\end_inset

,
 no questions there.
 But the statistic we are interested in makes no reference to the existence of 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\star}$
\end_inset

 at all.
 Indeed,
 the resulting likelihood ignores everything that isn't observed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This appears to be related to my problem where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimator doesn't the required information.
 The only obvious way to fix this is through the prior.
 Let's start with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x,y\mid\theta,y^{\star})$
\end_inset

.
 The next step is to handle 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\star}$
\end_inset

 by marginalizing it.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x,y\mid\theta)=\sum_{y^{\star}}p(x,y\mid\theta,y^{\star})p(y^{\star}\mid\theta),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y^{\star}|\theta)$
\end_inset

 is the parameter we wish to estimate?
 No,
 we wish to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y^{\star}\mid\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $p(y^{\star}=1|\theta)=\int\theta(x)dx.$
\end_inset

 However,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x,y\mid y^{\star},\theta)=\frac{p(y^{\star}\mid x,\theta)p(x)(1-\pi(x))1[y=\text{NA}]+p(y^{\star}\mid x,\theta)p(x)\pi(x)1[y=y^{\star}]}{p(y^{\star}\mid\theta)},
\]

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p(x,y\mid\theta) & = & \sum_{y^{\star}}p(x,y\mid\theta,y^{\star})p(y^{\star}\mid\theta)\\
 & = & \sum_{y^{\star}}p(y^{\star}\mid x,\theta)p(x)(1-\pi(x))1[y=\text{NA}]+p(y^{\star}\mid x,\theta)p(x)\pi(x)1[y=y^{\star}]\\
 & = & [p(x)(1-\pi(x))]^{(1-R)}[p(y\mid x,\theta)p(x)\pi(x)]^{R}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Just as before,
 so we don't really gain any information about 
\begin_inset Formula $y^{\star}$
\end_inset

 here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
